    "body": "I've noticed that the Cython compiler allows one to compile a file having the wrong extension--.py instead of .pyx--with the former situation producing spurious tracebacks.  Renaming the file eliminates the tracebacks.  I recommend that the Cython compiler either provide the same behavior regardless of the file\r\nextension, or refuse to accept a file having the wrong extension.  If compilation of a file with the .py extension is not necessarily a mistake, the Cython docs should be updated to explain what this does.",
    "closed_at": "2017-08-16T03:59:28Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "body": "Cython compiles .py files that are valid Python files (e.g. without extensions like the \"cdef\" keywords, though if there's a corresponding .pxd file that'll be applied). See http://cython.readthedocs.io/en/latest/src/tutorial/pure.html\r\n\r\nRegardless, we shouldn't be crashing with tracebacks. Can you give us an example? ",
